@namespace MindAttic.Ideas.Component.IdeasBrochure
@inherits ComponentBase

<link rel="stylesheet" href="/_ideas/Component/ideasbrochure/1/brochure.css" />

<div class="ibr">

  <!-- ── Hero ── -->
  <section class="ibr-hero">
    <p class="ibr-hero-eyebrow">A Content Management System for the post-framework era</p>
    <h1 class="ibr-hero-title">
      <span class="ibr-hero-wordmark">MindAttic</span><span class="ibr-hero-dot">.</span><span class="ibr-hero-ideas">Ideas</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="ibr-hero-tagline">
      Upload a <code class="ibr-code-inline">.idea</code> package. It goes live.
      No restart. No pipeline. No ceremony.
    </p>
    <div class="ibr-hero-badges">
      <span class="ibr-badge">Hot-load</span>
      <span class="ibr-badge">Zero-redeploy</span>
      <span class="ibr-badge">Scoped CSS &amp; JS</span>
      <span class="ibr-badge">Free-form pages</span>
      <span class="ibr-badge">.NET 10 / Blazor</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Three primitives ── -->
  <section class="ibr-section">
    <h2 class="ibr-section-title">Three honest primitives</h2>
    <p class="ibr-section-lead">
      A CMS has exactly one job: connect content to presentation without getting in the way.
      That takes three things and nothing else.
    </p>
    <div class="ibr-pillars">
      <article class="ibr-pillar">
        <div class="ibr-pillar-label">Page</div>
        <h3 class="ibr-pillar-title">Free-form HTML in a database row</h3>
        <p>
          One table. One row per page. No zones. No panes. No layout XML. A page is a slug,
          a title, and a body that can embed widget tokens anywhere in the markup. The browser
          <code class="ibr-code-inline">&lt;title&gt;</code> is its own standalone field.
          That's it.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="ibr-pillar">
        <div class="ibr-pillar-label">Plugin / Component</div>
        <h3 class="ibr-pillar-title">A self-contained <code class="ibr-code-inline">.idea</code> zip</h3>
        <p>
          A single archive: a compiled Blazor component, a CSS file scoped to a widget-specific
          class prefix, and JavaScript in an IIFE. Installed live with no redeploy.
          Versioned with a whole number — V1, V2, never 2.6.0.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="ibr-pillar">
        <div class="ibr-pillar-label">Theme</div>
        <h3 class="ibr-pillar-title">A visual wrapper — nothing more</h3>
        <p>
          Themes control typography, color, and the chrome around a page's body. They never
          touch the admin UI. They never own routes. A broken theme cannot lock you out of
          your site.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Token grammar ── -->
  <section class="ibr-section">
    <h2 class="ibr-section-title">The token grammar</h2>
    <p class="ibr-section-lead">
      Compose a page by writing free-form HTML and dropping tokens wherever a widget should appear.
      No visual builder required. No drag-and-drop. No layout system.
    </p>
    <div class="ibr-two-col">
      <div>
        <p class="ibr-caption">A page body (authored in the admin editor):</p>
        <pre class="ibr-code-block"><span class="ibr-ck-tag">&lt;h2&gt;</span>Software Projects<span class="ibr-ck-tag">&lt;/h2&gt;</span>
<span class="ibr-ck-token">{{ MindAttic.Ideas.Component.TabBoard }}</span>

<span class="ibr-ck-tag">&lt;h2&gt;</span>Selected Work<span class="ibr-ck-tag">&lt;/h2&gt;</span>
<span class="ibr-ck-token">{{ MindAttic.Ideas.Component.Gallery }}</span>

<span class="ibr-ck-comment">&lt;!-- Pin a specific version: --&gt;</span>
<span class="ibr-ck-token">{{ MindAttic.Ideas.Plugin.Tooltip.V2 }}</span>

<span class="ibr-ck-comment">&lt;!-- Pass attributes to a widget: --&gt;</span>
<span class="ibr-ck-token">{{ MindAttic.Ideas.Component.Hero title="Hello" }}</span></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="ibr-token-rules">
        <p class="ibr-caption">Resolution rules:</p>
        <ul class="ibr-rule-list">
          <li><strong>Floating</strong> — no version suffix → latest installed version</li>
          <li><strong>Pinned</strong> — <code class="ibr-code-inline">.V2</code> suffix → that exact version, always</li>
          <li><strong>Missing</strong> → a placeholder renders instead of a crash; the admin inbox gets an alert</li>
          <li><strong>Disabled</strong> → same graceful degradation; the page still serves</li>
          <li><strong>Attributes</strong> → passed directly to the Blazor component's <code class="ibr-code-inline">[Parameter]</code> properties</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── .idea package anatomy ── -->
  <section class="ibr-section">
    <h2 class="ibr-section-title">Anatomy of a <code class="ibr-code-inline">.idea</code> package</h2>
    <p class="ibr-section-lead">
      Every widget is one file. Drop it in Admin → Upload and it is live within the same request
      cycle — no IIS restart, no config change, no app pool recycle.
    </p>
    <div class="ibr-two-col">
      <pre class="ibr-code-block"><span class="ibr-ck-dir">MindAttic.Ideas.Component.TabBoard.V1.idea  (zip)</span>
├── <span class="ibr-ck-key">idea.json</span>
│   <span class="ibr-ck-tag">{</span>
│     <span class="ibr-ck-key">"key"</span>: <span class="ibr-ck-val">"tabboard"</span>,
│     <span class="ibr-ck-key">"version"</span>: <span class="ibr-ck-val">1</span>,
│     <span class="ibr-ck-key">"displayName"</span>: <span class="ibr-ck-val">"Tab Board"</span>,
│     <span class="ibr-ck-key">"category"</span>: <span class="ibr-ck-val">"Component"</span>
│   <span class="ibr-ck-tag">}</span>
├── <span class="ibr-ck-dir">bin/</span>
│   └── MindAttic.Ideas.Component.TabBoard.dll
└── <span class="ibr-ck-dir">wwwroot/</span>
    ├── tabboard.css  <span class="ibr-ck-comment">← .ma-tabs-*  (never leaks)</span>
    └── tabboard.js   <span class="ibr-ck-comment">← (function(){ … })()  (no globals)</span></pre>
      <div>
        <h3 class="ibr-sub-title">What happens at install time</h3>
        <ol class="ibr-numbered">
          <li>The zip is validated against the manifest schema.</li>
          <li>The DLL is loaded into a <strong>Collectible Assembly Load Context</strong> — isolated from the host and garbage-collected when replaced.</li>
          <li>Static assets are mounted at <code class="ibr-code-inline">/_ideas/Component/tabboard/1/</code>.</li>
          <li>The widget is registered in the in-memory content catalog.</li>
          <li>Any page containing <code class="ibr-code-inline">{{ … TabBoard }}</code> resolves it on the next render — without touching the page record.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── DNN section ── -->
  <section class="ibr-section ibr-section--dnn">
    <h2 class="ibr-section-title">They saw the future. The technology wasn't ready.</h2>
    <div class="ibr-two-col ibr-dnn-cols">
      <div>
        <p>
          DotNetNuke launched in 2003 and had a genuinely revolutionary idea: a CMS where every
          capability arrived as an installable zip package. Upload a module, it's live. No developer
          required. No deployment pipeline. No server access needed. They saw exactly what the
          web should be — and they were right.
        </p>
        <p>
          But the technology of the era made clean execution impossible. WebForms required every
          module to participate in an elaborate page-event lifecycle. CSS had no isolation mechanism.
          JavaScript had no module system. And most fatally, the <em>Skin</em> system wrapped the
          entire page <em>including the admin chrome</em>. A broken skin meant you couldn't access
          your own admin panel to fix it. You were locked out of your own site.
        </p>
        <blockquote class="ibr-quote">
          The concept was correct. The execution was a prisoner of 2003.
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          MindAttic.Ideas revisits that vision with two decades of better tools. The installable
          package idea is intact. Everything else is solved:
        </p>
        <ul class="ibr-dnn-list">
          <li>Blazor's component model gives widgets genuinely isolated render trees</li>
          <li>A per-widget CSS class prefix means <code class="ibr-code-inline">.ma-tabs-*</code> cannot affect <code class="ibr-code-inline">.ma-footer-*</code></li>
          <li>JavaScript in an IIFE means no global variable conflicts between widgets</li>
          <li>The admin UI lives on its own route prefix, styled by a fixed system stylesheet — never a theme</li>
          <li>Collectible Assembly Load Contexts mean a widget DLL is isolated and garbage-collected when replaced</li>
          <li>Pages are free-form HTML — no zone/pane/slot XML, because HTML and CSS already solve layout</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ibr-dnn-card">
        <h3 class="ibr-dnn-card-title">What DNN got right</h3>
        <ul class="ibr-check-list ibr-check-list--yes">
          <li>Capabilities as installable zip packages</li>
          <li>Hot-install without server restarts</li>
          <li>Content independent of presentation</li>
          <li>Portal-based multi-tenancy vision</li>
          <li>A module marketplace concept</li>
          <li>Versioned modules</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="ibr-dnn-card-title ibr-mt">What held it back</h3>
        <ul class="ibr-check-list ibr-check-list--no">
          <li>Themes wrapped the admin UI (fatal)</li>
          <li>No CSS isolation between modules</li>
          <li>No JS isolation — globals everywhere</li>
          <li>Zone/pane layout system instead of free HTML</li>
          <li>WebForms postback lifecycle complexity</li>
          <li>Module API tightly coupled to DNN internals</li>
          <li>Technical debt outpaced the vision</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

